{% if "command_injection" in data.contains_type %}
    <li>{% trans %}We identified that the following URLs are vulnerable to OS command injection:{% endtrans %}
        <ul>
            {% for report in data.reports %}
                {% if report.report_type == "command_injection" %}
                    {% for message in report.additional_data.result %}
                        <li>
                            {{ message.url }}
                            {% if message.code == report.additional_data.statements.command_injection_time_based %}
                                :
                                {% trans trimmed %}
                                    This was detected using a time-based (blind) technique: an injected sleep command
                                    caused a reproducible delay in the response, which shows the server executed it even
                                    though the command output is not visible in the response.
                                {% endtrans %}
                            {% endif %}
                        </li>
                    {% endfor %}
                {% endif %}
            {% endfor %}
        </ul>
        <p>
            {% trans trimmed %}
                OS command injection occurs when user input is passed to a system shell without proper validation,
                allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary operating system commands on the server. This can lead to full
                server compromise, data theft, and lateral movement inside the network. To fix this, avoid passing user
                input to shell commands; where that is unavoidable, use parameterized APIs and strictly validate and
                whitelist all input.
            {% endtrans %}
        </p>
    </li>
{% endif %}
